Exploration

Before starting out on any survey analysis it is always a good idea to explore what your data shows.

Let’s take a look at the journalistic formats results

Main focus is to work out whether our different journalistic formats impact satisfaction with our journalism

We can see that live events has had hardly any responses due to large number of NAs

We also see that live blogs, podcasts, and videos have a high proportions of nas as well as do not use these. This is good to keep in mind should we wish to do a regression analysis because they will count as missing data

Let’s explore further by looking into what % of users are aware of the particular format

journo_formats %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(does_use = if_else(value == "I haven't encountered / do not use these", F, T)) %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  summarise(prop = n / sum(n),
            does_use = does_use) %>% 
  group_by(does_use, name) %>% 
  summarise(prop = sum(prop)) %>% 
  filter(does_use == T) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(reorder(name, + prop) , prop)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'name'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'does_use'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
